</ol>

<hr>

<h2 id="recording">1. Recording an Inspection</h2>
<ol>
    <li>Go to <a href="/Apiary/inspections/new">/Apiary/inspections/new</a>.</li>
    <li>Select the <strong>Hive</strong> from the dropdown.</li>
    <li>Set the <strong>Inspection Date</strong>.</li>
    <li>Record overall observations: queen seen, brood pattern, temperament, population estimate, disease/pest signs.</li>
    <li>Add <strong>Inspection Details</strong> per box: box number, frame observations, honey and brood coverage.</li>
    <li>Add a <strong>Feeding Record</strong> if you fed the hive (type, quantity, notes).</li>
    <li>Click <strong>Save Inspection</strong>. All records are saved in a single database transaction — if any part fails, nothing is saved (data is not left in a partial state).</li>
</ol>

<hr>

<h2 id="viewing">2. Viewing an Inspection</h2>
<p>
Click any inspection in the list at <a href="/Apiary/inspections">/Apiary/inspections</a> to see the full record.
The view page shows:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>Overall inspection observations</li>
    <li>The <strong>visual hive diagram</strong> (see below)</li>
    <li>Per-box and per-frame details</li>
    <li>Feeding records</li>
    <li>Edit and delete actions (admin only)</li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h2 id="hive-diagram">3. Hive Diagram</h2>
<p>
Each inspection view includes a visual diagram of the hive. The diagram renders the hive's box and
frame configuration as a graphical representation, showing:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>Number of boxes (supers and brood boxes)</li>
    <li>Frame-level state where recorded: drawn comb, brood, honey, pollen</li>
    <li>Queen position if noted</li>
</ul>
<p>
The diagram is generated by the <code>_hive_diagram.tt</code> partial template which is included
on both the inspection view page and the hive management page.
</p>

<hr>

<h2 id="calendar">4. Inspection Calendar</h2>
<p>
<a href="/Apiary/inspection_calendar">/Apiary/inspection_calendar</a> shows a calendar grid with inspection
dates highlighted. Click any date with an inspection to jump to that inspection's record.
This gives you a quick overview of inspection frequency and history for all hives.
</p>

<hr>

<h2 id="reports">5. Inspection Reports</h2>
<p>
Printable inspection reports are available at <a href="/Apiary/inspections/reports">/Apiary/inspections/reports</a>.
Reports show all inspections in a formatted layout suitable for:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>Printing and filing</li>
    <li>Sharing with apiary associations or regulators</li>
    <li>Year-end review</li>
</ul>
<p>Use your browser's Print function (Ctrl+P) — print CSS applies a clean layout.</p>

<hr>

<h2 id="feeding">6. Feeding Records</h2>
<p>
Feeding is recorded as part of an inspection. Each feeding record captures:
</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Feed type</strong> — e.g. sugar syrup (1:1 or 2:1), pollen patty, fondant</li>
    <li><strong>Quantity</strong> — amount given</li>
    <li><strong>Notes</strong> — any observations about how the feed was taken</li>
</ul>
<p>
Multiple feeding records can be added to a single inspection (e.g. if multiple hives in the same yard were fed).
</p>

<hr>

<h2 id="queens">7. Queen Events</h2>
<p>
Queen events (swarm, supersedure, re-queen, queen loss, queen introduction) are tracked separately
from inspections via the <strong>QueenEvent</strong> and <strong>QueenHiveAssignment</strong> records.
These can be accessed through the hive management pages under <a href="/Apiary/HiveManagement">/Apiary/HiveManagement</a>.
</p>
<p>
Queen-to-hive assignment history is maintained in <code>QueenHiveAssignment</code>, so you can trace which queen
was in which hive at any point in time.
</p>

<hr>

